{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17604581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17604581"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:55:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:55:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15842"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15842"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.82,0,0.09,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8533"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71565"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8533"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57061"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8503"},{"type":"tags","id":"8594"},{"type":"tags","id":"10146"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20478"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71565"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the implantation window, the endometrium undergoes significant changes to prepare for potential blastocyst implantation. These changes are primarily driven by progesterone from the corpus luteum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the endometrial changes during the implantation window?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased endometrial blood flow","Increased secretion of glycogen-rich materials","Reduced expression of adhesion molecules","Thinning of the endometrial lining","Reduced cytokine production"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the implantation window, the endometrium becomes maximally receptive to blastocyst implantation. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased secretion of glycogen-rich materials\u003C/strong\u003E from endometrial glands provides nutrition for the developing blastocyst.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options are physiologically inaccurate because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased endometrial blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E - vascularity increases to support implantation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced expression of adhesion molecules\u003C/strong\u003E - adhesion molecules like integrins increase to facilitate attachment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThinning of the endometrial lining\u003C/strong\u003E - the endometrium reaches maximum thickness during this time\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced cytokine production \u003C/strong\u003E- an increase in IL-1 and IL-6 production which are involved in the maternal-embryo interaction during implantation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe endometrium transforms into decidua under the influence of progesterone, with three distinct regions forming: the decidua basalis (beneath the implantation site), decidua capsularis (overlying the implantation site), and decidua parietalis (remainder of the uterine cavity).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The implantation window occurs between days 6-10 after ovulation when the endometrium is most receptive to blastocyst implantation","The decidua is the modified endometrium of pregnancy, divided into basalis, capsularis, and parietalis regions","Progesterone from the corpus luteum is essential for maintaining the decidua in early pregnancy"],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Ochoa-Bernal MA, Fazleabas AT. Physiologic Events of Embryo Implantation and Decidualization in Human and Non-Human Primates. International Journal of Molecular Sciences [Internet]. 2020 Mar 13;21(6). Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7139778/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57061"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15842"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57061"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-19T14:39:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-19T14:39:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8533"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71565"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","posit